This phrase is so overused, it has become an excuse to be lazy in many cases.<p>Look how Cory Doctorow works:<p>&quot;
The write it now and fix it later approach sounds perfectly reasonable to me, but then Doctorow pushes it to an extreme. For instance, I wrote Homeland [2013] while I was touring Germany to publicise Little Brother [2008]. I had a translator, wed visit lots of schools, and so Id be speaking English half the time and hed be speaking German half the time, and Id write the book while he was speaking German.
&quot;<p><a href="http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/9a344ea2-e8af-11e2-aead-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2eUDlhKGn" rel="nofollow">http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/9a344ea2-e8af-11e2-aead-00144feabd...</a><p>He is 27 women making 4 babies a week.  And he manages to make breakfast for them all every morning too ;-)
